1.3 Building a plot

1.3.1 Calling ggplot()

ggplot(tidy_pop)

1.3.2 Adding aesthetics

ggplot(tidy_pop,
  aes(x = year, #<<
      y = pop) #<<
  )

1.3.3 Choosing the geometry (geom)

ggplot(tidy_pop,
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop)
  ) +
  geom_point()

1.3.4 Adding a third variable, country, as a colour.

ggplot(tidy_pop,
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      color = country) 
  ) + 
  geom_point()

1.3.5 Adding a line to the plot

ggplot(tidy_pop,
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      color = country) 
  ) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()
## geom_path: Each group consists of only one observation. Do you need to adjust
## the group aesthetic?

1.3.6 Adding a line to the plot, group by country.

ggplot(tidy_pop,
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      color = country) 
  ) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(
    aes(group = country))

1.3.7 Storing a plot

g <- ggplot(tidy_pop, 
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      color = country) 
  ) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(
    aes(group = country))

g

1.3.8 Specifying the aesthetics for each geometry.

g <- ggplot() +
  geom_point(
    data = tidy_pop, 
    aes(x = year, 
      y = pop, 
      color = country) 
  ) +
  geom_line(
    data = tidy_pop, 
    aes(x = year, 
      y = pop, 
      color = country, 
      group = country) 
    )

g

1.3.9 Adding more data. Creating tidy_pop2

tidy_pop2 <- left_join(tidy_pop, select(gapminder, country, continent))
## Joining, by = "country"
g <- ggplot(tidy_pop2) +
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      color = country) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(group = country))

1.3.10 Using Facets

g + facet_wrap(~ country)

1.3.11 Using facet_grid, two variables.

g + facet_grid(continent ~ country)

1.3.12 Adding labels

(g <- g + labs(x = "Year", y = "Population (millions)"))

1.3.13 Showing coordinates

g + coord_flip()

1.3.14 Changing the color scale

g + scale_color_manual(values = c("peru", "pink", "plum"))

1.3.15 Changing the scale of the y

g + scale_y_log10()

1.3.16 Changing the scale of the x

g + scale_x_discrete(labels = c("MCMXCVII", "MMII", "MMVII"))

1.3.17 Changing the theme

g + theme_bw()

1.3.18 Changing the theme (fonts and colours)

g + theme_bw() + theme(text = element_text(colour = "hotpink", size = 20))

1.3.19 Setting an overall theme:

my_theme <- theme_bw() +
  theme(
    text = element_text(size = 12),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = 'grey80'), 
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

theme_set(my_theme)

1.3.20 Making the plot with the new theme

theme_set(my_theme)
g

1.3.21 Changing the position of the legend

theme_set(my_theme)
g + theme(legend.position = 'bottom')

2.1 Exercises 1

Add the title âLife Expectancy in the Americas 1952 vs 2007â using ggtitle().

gapminder %>%
  filter(continent == "Americas", 
         year %in% c(1952, 2007)) %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(year)) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(y = country, 
                             x = lifeExp, 
                             colour = year)) +
    labs(x = "Life Expectancy", 
         y = "Country", 
         colour = "Year")

2.2 Exercise 2

  • Rerun the plot removing fct_reorder, what does fct_reorder do?

  • Rerun the plot again this time removing coord_flip(). What does the function coord_flip() change in the plot?

gap_lifeExpdiff_df <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(life_exp_diff = max(lifeExp) - min(lifeExp)) %>% 
  top_n(n = 5)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## Selecting by life_exp_diff
p1 <- ggplot(gap_lifeExpdiff_df) +
    geom_col(mapping = aes(x = fct_reorder(country, life_exp_diff), y = life_exp_diff), fill = "blue") +
    labs(y = "Difference in Life Expectancy", x = "") +
    ggtitle("Difference in Life Expectancy", sub = "Top 5 countries with the largest difference (1952-2007)") +
    ylim(0, 40)

p1 + coord_flip()

Excellent tutorial by Jenny Bryan âBe the Boss of your factorsâ

4.3.22 Whatâs the difference between a bar chart and a pie chart?

ggplot(americas,
  aes(x = " ", #<<
      y = pop,
      fill = fct_reorder(
        country, pop) 
      )
  ) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(fill = "Country") +
  coord_polar(theta = "y", start = 0) #<<

4.3.23 What if we want to see each year?

ggplot(americas,
  aes(x = " ", 
      y = pop,
      fill = fct_reorder(
        country, pop) 
      )
  ) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(fill = "Country") +
  coord_polar(theta = "y", start = 0) +
  facet_wrap(~year) #<<

Short Aside: Why you should consider alternatives to pie charts

4.3.24 Returning to bar charts

Bars are âstackedâ, can we separate?

4.3.25 Changing the position using âdodgeâ

ggplot(americas,
  aes(x = year,
      y = pop,
      fill = fct_reorder(  
        country, pop) 
      )
  ) +
  geom_col(
    position = "dodge") + #<<
  labs(fill = "Country")

position = "dodge" places objects next to each other instead of overlapping

What is scientific notation anyway?

ggplot(americas,

       )

ggplot aesthetics can take expressions! Still, it might be easier to see countries individually

4.3.27 Using facet_wrap() to create individual plots

ggplot(americas,
